{{Group
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} is a threat group that has been active since at least 2009 and was reportedly responsible for the November 2014 destructive wiper attack against Sony Pictures Entertainment. It was responsible for a campaign known as Operation Blockbuster. Malware used by {{LinkThisPage}} correlates to other reported campaigns, including Operation Flame, Operation 1Mission, Operation Troy, DarkSeoul, and Ten Days of Rain.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster]]
|AliasDescriptions={{Alias Description
|Alias=Lazarus Group
}}
|TechniqueObjects={{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1027
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware uses multiple types of encryption and encoding in its malware files, including AES, Caracachs, RC4, basic XOR with constant 0xA7, and other techniques.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster]][[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]][[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster RATs]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1094
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware uses a unique form of communication encryption that mimics TLS but uses a different encryption method, evading SSL man-in-the-middle decryption attacks.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1032
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware uses Caracachs encryption to encrypt C2 payloads.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1107
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware contains "suicide scripts" to delete malware binaries from the victim. It also uses secure file deletion to delete files from the victim.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1083
|Description=Several {{LinkThisPage}} malware samples use a common function to identify target files by their extension. {{LinkThisPage}} malware families also enumerate files and directories on lettered drives.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1050
|Description=Several {{LinkThisPage}} malware families install themselves as new services on victims.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Destructive Malware]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1059
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware uses cmd.exe to execute commands on victims.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Destructive Malware]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1082
|Description=Several {{LinkThisPage}} malware families collect information on the type and version of the victim OS, as well as the victim computer name and CPU information.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Destructive Malware]][[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1099
|Description=Several {{LinkThisPage}} malware families use timestomping, including modifying the last write timestamp of a specified Registry key to a random date, as well as copying the timestamp for legitimate .exe files (such as calc.exe or mspaint.exe) to its dropped files.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Destructive Malware]][[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1098
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware WhiskeyDelta-Two contains a function that attempts to rename the administrator’s account.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Destructive Malware]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1024
|Description=Several {{LinkThisPage}} malware families encrypt C2 traffic using custom code that uses XOR with an ADD operation and XOR with a SUB operation.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Destructive Malware]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1105
|Description=Several {{LinkThisPage}} malware families are capable of downloading and executing binaries from its C2 server.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Destructive Malware]][[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1089
|Description=Various {{LinkThisPage}} malware modifies the Windows firewall to allow incoming connections or disable it entirely using {{LinkByID|S0108}}. [[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]] [[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Tools]] {{LinkThisPage}} malware TangoDelta attempts to terminate various processes associated with McAfee.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Tools]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1057
|Description=Several {{LinkThisPage}} malware families gather a list of running processes on a victim system and send it to their C2 server.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1010
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware IndiaIndia obtains and sends to its C2 server the title of the window for each running process.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]] The KilaAlfa keylogger also reports the title of the window in the foreground.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Tools]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1016
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware IndiaIndia obtains and sends to its C2 server information about the first network interface card’s configuration, including IP address, gateways, subnet mask, DHCP information, and whether WINS is available.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1012
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware IndiaIndia checks Registry keys within HKCU and HKLM to determine if certain applications are present, including SecureCRT, Terminal Services, RealVNC, TightVNC, UltraVNC, Radmin, mRemote, TeamViewer, FileZilla, pcAnyware, and Remote Desktop.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1002
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware IndiaIndia saves information gathered about the victim to a file that is compressed with Zlib, encrypted, and uploaded to a C2 server.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]] {{LinkThisPage}} malware RomeoDelta archives specified directories in .zip format, encrypts the .zip file, and uploads it to its C2 server.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster RATs]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1022
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware IndiaIndia saves information gathered about the victim to a file that is compressed with Zlib, encrypted, and uploaded to a C2 server.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]] {{LinkThisPage}} malware RomeoDelta archives specified directories in .zip format, encrypts the .zip file, and uploads it to its C2 server.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster RATs]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1074
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware IndiaIndia saves information gathered about the victim to a file that is saved in the %TEMP% directory, then compressed, encrypted, and uploaded to a C2 server.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=Technique/T1041
|Description={{LinkThisPage}} malware IndiaIndia saves information gathered about the victim to a file that is uploaded to one of its 10 C2 servers.[[CiteRef::Novetta Blockbuster Loaders]]
}}{{Technique Object
|Technique=From local system
